'2022-04-21T13:51:40Z', 'closed_at': '2022-04-20T16:45:28Z', 'author_association': 'NONE', 'active_lock_reason': None, 'body': 'When selecting either GRS or GZRS redundancy, you can select _Make read access to data available in the event of regional unavailability_ option which the user _assumes_ converts it to RA-GRS or RA-GZRS.

Firstly, I believe the "unavailability" wording is incorrect. With RA-GRS and RA-GZRS you can always read your data in the secondary region even if the primary region is available, **not** just when it's unavailable. Therefore the wording is incorrect. See https://docs.microsoft.com/en-au/azure/storage/common/storage-redundancy#read-access-to-data-in-the-secondary-region for reference.

Secondly, it would be simply easier to add RA-GRS and RA-GZRS to the list of selectable redundancy options so that it's explicitly clear, rather than the user having to assume, what the _Make read access to data available in the event of regional unavailability_ option does.

'2022-04-20T16:45:26Z', 'closed_at': None, 'author_association': 'NONE', 'active_lock_reason': None, 'body': 'When selecting either GRS or GZRS redundancy, you can select _Make read access to data available in the event of regional unavailability_ option which the user _assumes_ converts it to RA-GRS or RA-GZRS.

Firstly, I believe the "unavailability" wording is incorrect. With RA-GRS and RA-GZRS you can always read your data in the secondary region even if the primary region is available, **not** just when it's unavailable. Therefore the wording is incorrect. See https://docs.microsoft.com/en-au/azure/storage/common/storage-redundancy#read-access-to-data-in-the-secondary-region for reference.

Secondly, it would be simply easier to add RA-GRS and RA-GZRS to the list of selectable redundancy options so that it's explicitly clear, rather than the user having to assume, what the _Make read access to data available in the event of regional unavailability_ option does.

answer is wrong:
> Can I use a VHD file in an Azure storage account to create a managed disk with a different subscription?
> Yes.

The Azure CLI gives this error when attempting this operation:

> Message: The source blob https://labtainersblob.blob.core.windows.net/labtainersblobcontainer/labtainersbase.vhd does not belong to a storage account in subscription 0b2f9b91-93da-4d14-8279-813a24bb4f51.

Try it yourself (first create a labtainerResources group):
```
#!/bin/bash
if [ "$#" -ne 1 ]; then
    echo "create_disk.sh <disk name>"
    exit
fi
disk=$1
az disk create -g labtainerResources -n $disk --source https://labtainersblob.blob.core.windows.net/labtainersblobcontainer/labtainersbase.vhd --output none
```

'2022-04-20T16:01:09Z', 'closed_at': None, 'author_association': 'NONE', 'active_lock_reason': None, 'body': 'The page does not include, nor goes into the configuration items on AD side: You can add the following items to PShell all of this: 

New-ADComputer <storage account name> -ServicePrincipalNames "cifs/storageaccountname.file.core.windows.net" -Path 'DN of OU path'
#(Make sure to add the $ sign to the computer object name)
Set-ADAccountPassword -Identity 'storage account name$ ‘
-Reset ‘
-NewPassword (ConvertTo-SecureString -AsPlainText "Key retrieved in earlier step" -Force)


On a computer with AD PShell cmd'lets or a DC

$DomainSID=(Get-ADDomain).DomainSid.Value
$DomainGUID= (Get-ADDomain).objectGuid.guid
$ADDomainName=(Get-ADDomain).DNSRoot
$ADNETBIOS=(Get-ADDomain).NetBiosName
$ADForest=(Get-ADDomain).Forest

$ObjectSID=(Get-ADComputer storageaccountname).SID.Value

And finally on a computer with access to AZ and Azure Subscription:

Set-AzStorageAccount `
        -ResourceGroupName "your-resource-group-name-here" `
        -Name "your-storage-account-name-here" `
        -EnableActiveDirectoryDomainServicesForFile $true `
        -ActiveDirectoryDomainName $ADDomainName `
        -ActiveDirectoryNetBiosDomainName $ADNetbios `
        -ActiveDirectoryForestName $ADForest `
        -ActiveDirectoryDomainGuid $DomainGUID `
        -ActiveDirectoryDomainsid $DomainSID `
        -ActiveDirectoryAzureStorageSid $ObjectSID

'2022-04-20T16:00:39Z', 'closed_at': None, 'author_association': 'NONE', 'active_lock_reason': None, 'body': 'If there are the supported version of execution environment (OS and PowerShell) about the script in "Option one (recommended): Use AzFilesHybrid PowerShell module", please add it in this document.
[Option one (recommended): Use AzFilesHybrid PowerShell module](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/storage/files/storage-files-identity-ad-ds-enable#option-one-recommended-use-azfileshybrid-powershell-module)

---
**Backgrounds**
We did step of "Option one (recommended): Use AzFilesHybrid PowerShell module", but they got error.
It seems it can't get "-ActiveDirectoryDomainSid $domainSid" of "Set-AzStorageAccount" command in "Join-AzStorageAccountForAuth" command.

In troubleshooting, we found that;
if they execute the command "$domainSid = $domainInformation.DomainSID.Value" in line 3766 of AzFilesHybrid.psm1 without ".Value", they can get the DomainSid correctly.

Our execution environment;
- PSVersion 7.1.0
- PSEdition Core
- GitCommitId 7.1.0
- OS Microsoft Windows 10.0.14393
- Platform Win32NT
- PSCompatibleVersions {1.0, 2.0, 3.0, 4.0…}
- PSRemotingProtocolVersion 2.3
- SerializationVersion 1.1.0.1
- WSManStackVersion 3.0

We used PSVersion 5.1 temporary, we success to execute the same command with ".Value" (default).


---

"For computer accounts, there is a default password expiration age set in AD at 30 days."

While computers change their passwords by default every 30 days, I did not think there was actually a default expiration period enforced by AD. 

https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/previous-versions/windows/it-pro/windows-server-2012-r2-and-2012/jj852252(v=ws.11)#default-values

It is best practice to set this policy and it is in several of the security baseline policies. But that does not make it a default.

'2022-04-20T15:57:34Z', 'closed_at': None, 'author_association': 'NONE', 'active_lock_reason': None, 'body': 'A customer recently created an Azure Files file share and joined the file share to azure AD: DS using this method. Everything worked, and the configuration showed it successfully joined.

However, users received the error "Access Denied" when attempting to map the share.

The Azure File Share diagnostics indicated it could not find the signedinuser's GUID sync'd to AzureAD:DS.

The best explanation support offered is that when an Azure File's share syncs with AD:DS it at one property for the users GUID and when it syncs with Azure AD:DS looks at different object property for the user's GUID.

When looking through the what is supported and what is not supported we don't see Azure AD: DS not supported, so the expectation was, "both ways work, there is nothing saying this isn't supported, but the Azure AD:DS method is a lot easier if you have azure ad:ds"

Moreover, after disabling the AD:DS method and enabling the Azure AD:DS method, authentication lost the password sync after some time (less than 4). Next, we used ADUC to remove the computer created when joining azure files and did another disable/enable for Azure AD:DS in azure files.

I think it's working now ;)

Here's the related service ticket for your reference
Trouble authenticating to Azure Files file share - TrackingID#2103040040008230

_Edit: Rephrased for clarity_

https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/storage/files/storage-sync-files-deployment-guide?tabs=azure-portal 

says that you should only setup additional servers after the initial sync. Step "Prerequisites 3" implies you setup all of the VM's before doing the initial file creation.

This is a critical difference; I would assume that "Onboarding with Azure File Sync" is more correct, and will preserve my ACL's better, but these two documents really should either use the same sequence, OR mention specifically why the sequence is more correct 'the other way'.

Most SMB (Small to Medium Businesses) are going to move to the cloud in the coming years, so the normal activity is:

1. OnPrem AD.
2. Create all this "Stuff" in Azure
3. Copy your files to this "Stuff"
4. Setup access for others direct to the crowd WITH the current ACL's.

At a meta level, these are the steps. I think an overview would be great if it could resolve this; this article implies it happens after step 2, but the linked article implies AAD DS is setup after step 3, and gives a good reason for doing so.

Thank you!

running in azure, which also is a host for docker containers.

I hit issues where docker containers running .net core applications could not write files to the share. There is a github issue here:

https://github.com/dotnet/runtime/issues/42790#issuecomment-817758887

The solution is to make sure that `nobrl` is included as an option for the cifs mount.

'2022-04-20T15:56:46Z', 'closed_at': None, 'author_association': 'NONE', 'active_lock_reason': None, 'body': 'Found it impossible to mount this on my mac on my home machine - and I believe I know why.

You have a point here:
"Ensure port 445 is open: SMB communicates over TCP port 445. On your client machine (the Mac), check to make sure your firewall is not blocking TCP port 445."

*I* don't block it, but guess who does.. my ISP, to protect me from open file shares. I assume this is common, and I recommend reflecting in that point that your ISP commonly blocks file sharing ports such as 445 and you may find it impossible to mount an azure drive on MacOS (and other OS's would be the same I imagine - you may want to document this on the linux/win pages too)

'2022-04-20T15:56:25Z', 'closed_at': None, 'author_association': 'NONE', 'active_lock_reason': None, 'body': 'As a Microsoft Azure Support Engineer, I worked on the case 2108270050000274 recently, it might be a good idea to describe how to create a new AD User in AD and what data to include when customers need to enable the AD DS with ServiceLogonAccount option, by leaving out the “-trustedForDelegation” parameter from the “New-ADUser” command specified in the AZFilesHybrid PowerShell module (file AzFilesHybird.psm1).

This customer ran into an issue when running the "Join-AzStorageAccountForAuth" command with error: "New-ADUser: A required privilege is not held by the client."

Following part:

# Create the identity in Active Directory.    
    try
    {
        switch ($ObjectType) {
            "ServiceLogonAccount" {
                Write-Verbose -Message "`$ServiceAccountName is $StorageAccountName"

                if ($null -ne $userSpnMatch) {
                    $userSpnMatch.AllowReversiblePasswordEncryption = $false
                    $userSpnMatch.PasswordNeverExpires = $true
                    $userSpnMatch.Description = "Service logon account for Azure storage account $StorageAccountName."
                    $userSpnMatch.Enabled = $true
                    $userSpnMatch.TrustedForDelegation = $true
                    Set-ADUser -Instance $userSpnMatch -ErrorAction Stop
                } else {
                    New-ADUser `
                        -SamAccountName $ADObjectName `
                        -Path $path `
                        -Name $ADObjectName `
                        -AccountPassword $fileServiceAccountPwdSecureString `
                        -AllowReversiblePasswordEncryption $false `
                        -PasswordNeverExpires $true `
                        -Description "Service logon account for Azure storage account $StorageAccountName." `
                        -ServicePrincipalNames $spnValue `
                        -Server $Domain `
                        -Enabled $true `
                        -TrustedForDelegation $true `
                        -ErrorAction Stop
                }

I would appreciate it if you could include this relevant content as soon as possible to help customers. 

Thanks in advance. Kind regards.

'2022-04-20T15:55:38Z', 'closed_at': None, 'author_association': 'NONE', 'active_lock_reason': None, 'body': 'Hello!

This document needs to be updated.
When we have on-prem AD Syncing with Azure AD, if we try to grant share level permission with RBAC, it only works with groups if we use an on-prem AD group with scope Universal. Groups with either Local or Global scopes don’t work.
Also, based on my testing, only convert group scope does not work. We need to have a group which already has Universal scope before it’s synced to Azure AD. Maybe also troubleshooting doc should be updated to include that.
This is not mentioned at document.

Rafael Oliveira

I just had a case where the customer's users could not access the share after giving their group permission to do so. 

The root cause turned out to be the AD group type was "local domain".  Once this was changed to type "Universal", it worked fine. 

There was no mention of this requirement. 

In addition, it allowed the user to assign the "local domain" group without error.  

Please update this document to mention the group type needs to be Universal. 

thanks!!

'comments': 2, 'created_at': '2021-04-23T17:45:12Z', 'updated_at': '2022-04-20T15:40:51Z', 'closed_at': None, 'author_association': 'NONE', 'active_lock_reason': None, 'body': '[Enter feedback here]
For running below commands, require az login from the VM. Which requires az module to be installed on the server. Instead, we can hardcode some of the variables


Instead of

httpEndpoint=$(az storage account show \
    --resource-group $resourceGroupName \
    --name $storageAccountName \
    --query "primaryEndpoints.file" | tr -d '"')

Use this

httpEndpoint="https://"Storage Account Name".file.core.windows.net/"



Instead of 

storageAccountKey=$(az storage account keys list \
    --resource-group $resourceGroupName \
    --account-name $storageAccountName \
    --query "[0].value" | tr -d '"')

Use this

storageAccountKey="giveDirectKeyHere"

Note: Get storage account Key > Storage account > Setting (Access Keys) > Show Keys > Copy Primary Key
Also note, it's unsafe to have the key in clear text, it's recommended to clear the history so that the key can't be retrieved from previous command

Just built this out with DFS-R.  Built an On-Premises File Server and an Azure Files Premium Storage Account.  We have 2 AD Sites, one for Azure and one for On-Premises and associated the Subnets to the appropriate AD Site.

When we add the On-Premises File Server UNC Path, it appropriately shows the AD Site within the DFS-N MMC.  However, when we add in the Azure Files UNC Path, it shows the AD Site as <Unknown>.  This would break DFS-N Referrals.

What we found is that if we create a Private Endpoint for that Azure Files Share in the VNET in which its address space is defined within AD Sites and Services, the DFS-N Console then correctly identifies the Azure Files UNC Path belonging to the Azure AD Site.  It seems as though this would be a requirement for DFS-N Referrals to work which would be something we'd want to have working in a scenario such as:

Using File Sync to replicate on-premises storage to Azure.  Add Azure Files into DFS-N so once Application Servers are migrated to Azure that they would now be redirected to using the Azure File Share as DFS-N would recognize the Application Server is in Azure and DFS-N points the recently migrated Application Server to the Azure File Server courtesy of the DFS-N referral process.

blobs you want the policy actions to apply to. The path must start with the blob container name. If no prefix match is specified, then the policy will apply to all the blobs in the storage account. The prefix match string format is [container name]/[blob name], where the container name or blob name can be a full or partial container name. Here I am adding some common misconceptions about the prefix match string.

Here are some common misconceptions about the prefix match string:
•	A prefix match string of container1/ applies to all blobs in the blob container named container1. A prefix match string of container1 (note that there is no trailing / character in the prefix string) applies to all blobs in all containers where the blob container name starts with the string container1. This includes blob containers named container11, container1234, container1ab, and so on.
•	A prefix match string of container1/sub1/ would apply to all blobs in the container with the name container1, whose blob names that start with the string sub1/ like container1/sub1/test.txt or container1/sub1/sub2/test.txt.
•	Wildcard character * - This doesn't mean 'matches one or more occurrences of any character'. The asterisk character * is a valid character in a blob name in Azure Storage. If added in a rule, it means match the blobs with the asterisk in the blob name.
•	Wildcard character ? - This doesn't mean 'match a single occurrence of any character'. The question mark character ? is a valid character in a blob name in Azure Storage. If added in a rule, it means match the blobs with a question mark in the blob name.
•	prefixMatch with != - The prefixMatch rules only consider positive (=) logical comparisons. Therefore, negative (!=) logical comparisons are ignored.", 'reactions': {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/MicrosoftDocs/azure-docs/issues/90880/reactions', 'total_count': 0, '+1': 0, '-1': 0, 'laugh': 0, 'hooray': 0, 'confused': 0, 'heart': 0, 'rocket': 0, 'eyes': 0}, 'timeline_url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/MicrosoftDocs/azure-docs/issues/90880/timeline', 'performed_via_github_app': None}, 'comment': {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/MicrosoftDocs/azure-docs/issues/comments/1101758929', 'html_url': 'https://github.com/MicrosoftDocs/azure-docs/pull/90880#issuecomment-1101758929', 'issue_url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/MicrosoftDocs/azure-docs/issues/90880', 'id': 1101758929, 'node_id': 'IC_kwDOBFUV4s5Bq4HR', 'user': {'login': 'tamram', 'id': 1189479, 'node_id': 'MDQ6VXNlcjExODk0Nzk=', 'avatar_url': 'https://avatars.githubusercontent.com/u/1189479?v=4', 'gravatar_id': '', 'url': 'https://api.github.com/users/tamram', 'html_url': 'https://github.com/tamram', 'followers_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/tamram/followers', 'following_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/tamram/following{/other_user}', 'gists_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/tamram/gists{/gist_id}', 'starred_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/tamram/starred{/owner}{/repo}', 'subscriptions_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/tamram/subscriptions', 'organizations_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/tamram/orgs', 'repos_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/tamram/repos', 'events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/tamram/events{/privacy}', 'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/tamram/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}, 'created_at': '2022-04-18T20:53:34Z', 'updated_at': '2022-04-18T20:53:34Z', 'author_association': 'CONTRIBUTOR', 'body': '@jainsourabh123 - Thanks for making these clarifications!

'body': '
In the doc section https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/storage/common/redundancy-migration?tabs=portal#switch-between-types-of-replication, there is a note that states that migrating from LRS to ZRS is not supported when NFSv4 is enabled on a File Share. PG has confirmed this is also not supported when NFSv3 is enabled on Blob storage so the docs should reflect that to reduce confusion.


---

'2022-03-30T18:42:39Z', 'closed_at': None, 'author_association': 'NONE', 'active_lock_reason': None, 'body': '
This document explains how to upload and update blob for concurrency. It does not address how to update blob that is already existing which requires reading with etag. FetchAttributes can be used for reading but it will populate properties and not get blob. One needs another call to get blob with conditional access. e.g. downloadasync with etag matching what we got after fetch attributes (since blob could have changed since getting etag). This is tricky and involves 2 calls. We can achieve with one call DownloadToStream method. Create a mem stream and use that method. It will also populate properties and so we can get etag. The doc for this method does not explain any of this. The documentation is pathetic. Needs improvement. I spent too long doing web search and experimentation to get this data. If doc explained all this, it would have made it easier to understand how to do this. Also, if blob does not exist, it will throw. How to determine 404 is not straight forward. One needs to look into inner exception and response and status code etc. Not obvious without experimentation. Please update doc

'comments': 1, 'created_at': '2022-03-26T20:48:50Z', 'updated_at': '2022-03-28T14:20:41Z', 'closed_at': None, 'author_association': 'NONE', 'active_lock_reason': None, 'body': "Azure Storage Accounts has a flag that you can set via Azure CLI called `publicNetworkAccess` (for example, see: https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/cli/azure/storage/account?view=azure-cli-latest#az-storage-account-create-optional-parameters). However, this flag is not discussed anywhere that I can find in current documentation about Storage Accounts and the description of the flag on the Azure CLI page provides no helpful information that cannot be gleaned by inference on the name of the flag itself.

CosmosDB would appear to have the same flag (see: https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/cosmos-db/how-to-configure-private-endpoints#blocking-public-network-access-during-account-creation) though the Azure CLI command for it doesn't seem to be the same.

All Storage Account security recommendations (https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/storage/blobs/security-recommendations) only discuss using the Storage Account's firewall to permit traffic to the endpoint or using Private Link. Setting the `publicNetworkAccess` flag to `Disabled` on a Storage Account (at creation or afterwards) causes the firewall ruleset to be ignored when addressing the public storage endpoint and it flips to Deny All, presumably only allowing communications through a Private Link Endpoint (which I haven't had a chance to test).

However, as mentioned, this flag is never discussed in any documentation, so its meaning is not completely clear, especially when looked at in the context of another, similar flag, `allowBlobPublicAccess` which does not affect the functionality of the firewall.

Also of note, this flag is not visible or settable anywhere in the Portal UI, and you cannot even see it in Resource Explorer. It is only exposed via the API (ARM templates/Azure CLI/PowerShell etc.)

Mentioning exactly what this flag does would be good, and even better would be to add a security recommendation to enable it when using Private Link (presuming that would be the actual recommendation).

'milestone': None, 'comments': 5, 'created_at': '2022-03-03T15:47:13Z', 'updated_at': '2022-03-22T16:01:30Z', 'closed_at': None, 'author_association': 'NONE', 'active_lock_reason': None, 'body': '
Hello team, 

I am a Azure Storage CSS engineer. We receive a good amount of cases where customers request Powershell or Azure CLI support in managing soft-deleted blobs when versioning is enabled also, for flat namespace accounts. We cannot assist them besides recommending they use .NET. We do not develop scripts for customers as part of CSS, so if they do not know .NET we cannot assist further.
For hierarchical namespace accounts the documentation contains many different options including PS and az-cli, and other languages.

Could you please look into adding script examples for Powershell and/or Azure-CLI on how to restore soft-deleted blobs in bulk for flat namespaces when versioning is also enabled? 

Thank you very much! This would be very helpful for our customers and would also help decrease volume of cases. 


---

'milestone': None, 'comments': 4, 'created_at': '2022-03-03T15:47:13Z', 'updated_at': '2022-03-16T18:34:26Z', 'closed_at': None, 'author_association': 'NONE', 'active_lock_reason': None, 'body': '
Hello team, 

I am a Azure Storage CSS engineer. We receive a good amount of cases where customers request Powershell or Azure CLI support in managing soft-deleted blobs when versioning is enabled also, for flat namespace accounts. We cannot assist them besides recommending they use .NET. We do not develop scripts for customers as part of CSS, so if they do not know .NET we cannot assist further.
For hierarchical namespace accounts the documentation contains many different options including PS and az-cli, and other languages.

Could you please look into adding script examples for Powershell and/or Azure-CLI on how to restore soft-deleted blobs in bulk for flat namespaces when versioning is also enabled? 

Thank you very much! This would be very helpful for our customers and would also help decrease volume of cases. 


---

'2022-03-15T20:58:35Z', 'closed_at': '2022-03-11T17:11:34Z', 'author_association': 'NONE', 'active_lock_reason': None, 'body': 'The call out box states on [this](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/storage/blobs/point-in-time-restore-overview) page states;

> When you perform a restore operation, Azure Storage blocks data operations on the blobs in the ranges being restored for the duration of the operation. Read, write, and delete operations are blocked in the primary location.

Suggesting in the first line that any blobs outside of the range will not be affected.

[This](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/backup/blob-restore#before-you-start) doc states;

> While a restore job is in progress, blobs in the storage cannot be read or written to.

Suggesting the whole storage account is blocked.

As Operational Backup uses point in time restore I would expect the statements to be the same. Can we get some clarity if the whole storage account or just the blobs in range are blocked and update accordingly please?


---

call out box states on [this](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/storage/blobs/point-in-time-restore-overview) page states;

> When you perform a restore operation, Azure Storage blocks data operations on the blobs in the ranges being restored for the duration of the operation. Read, write, and delete operations are blocked in the primary location.

Suggesting in the first line that any blobs outside of the range will not be affected.

[This](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/backup/blob-restore#before-you-start) doc states;

> While a restore job is in progress, blobs in the storage cannot be read or written to.

Suggesting the whole storage account is blocked.

As Operational Backup uses point in time restore I would expect the statements to be the same. Can we get some clarity if the whole storage account or just the blobs in range are blocked and update accordingly please?

Hello team, 

I am a Azure Storage CSS engineer. We receive a good amount of cases where customers request Powershell or Azure CLI support in managing soft-deleted blobs when versioning is enabled also, for flat namespace accounts. We cannot assist them besides recommending they use .NET. We do not develop scripts for customers as part of CSS, so if they do not know .NET we cannot assist further.
For hierarchical namespace accounts the documentation contains many different options including PS and az-cli, and other languages.

Could you please look into adding script examples for Powershell and/or Azure-CLI on how to restore soft-deleted blobs in bulk for flat namespaces when versioning is also enabled? 

Thank you very much! This would be very helpful for our customers and would also help decrease volume of cases.

'2022-02-16T01:14:41Z', 'closed_at': '2020-12-29T22:35:32Z', 'author_association': 'NONE', 'active_lock_reason': None, 'body': 'I have following variable in my ARM template:
```
 "serviceSasFunctionValues": {
          "canonicalizedResource": "[concat('/blob/', parameters('storageName'), '/', parameters('containerName'))]",
          "signedResource": "b",
          "signedPermission": "rwac",
          "signedExpiry": "2050-01-01T00:00:00Z"
        }
```
I'm using it to output SAS token string:
```
[listServiceSas(parameters('storageName'), '2018-02-01', variables('serviceSasFunctionValues')).serviceSasToken]
```
Generated SAS has following format:
```
sv=2015-04-05&sr=b&se=2050-01-01T00%3A00%3A00.0000000Z&sp=rwacu&sig=j%2Bn8B7DMTjuAjUQ1dVCzNzHXMznsgy%2FbOs04SHF4Tbo%3D
```
Note the `se` parameter format. C# client libraries (`Azure.Storage.Blobs.BlobServiceClient`) cannot accept it because they expect expiry time in other format:
```
// Azure.Storage.Sas.SasQueryParameters:
case Constants.Sas.Parameters.ExpiryTimeUpper:
DateTimeOffset.ParseExact(kv.Value, Constants.SasTimeFormat, CultureInfo.InvariantCulture);
// public const string SasTimeFormat = "yyyy-MM-ddTHH:mm:ssZ";
```

Looks like some inconsistency. Is there any way to configure `listServiceSas` to return date in correct format? Azure Portal does this just fine.

'2022-01-28T18:19:26Z', 'closed_at': '2022-01-27T18:53:39Z', 'author_association': 'CONTRIBUTOR', 'active_lock_reason': None, 'body': '
[Enter feedback here]

The page states:
"If you want to add or remove geo-replication or read access to the secondary region, you can use the Azure portal, PowerShell, or Azure CLI to update the replication setting. However, if you want to change how data is replicated in the primary region, by moving from LRS to ZRS or vice versa, then you must perform a manual migration."

A switch from ZRS to GZRS does not affect how data is replicated in the primary region (it remains ZRS there) according to this page: https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/storage/common/storage-redundancy?toc=/azure/storage/blobs/toc.json

"Geo-zone-redundant storage (GZRS) copies your data synchronously across three Azure availability zones in the primary region using ZRS."

The primary region remains ZRS in the switch from ZRS -> GZRS. So, why can this not be done in the portal. The page does not mention the ZRS -> GZRS scenario under any of the subsections detailing how to perform the change. It only appears in the table as requiring a live migration without further explanation.

# All SDK Contribution checklist:

This checklist is used to make sure that common guidelines for a pull request are followed.
- [ ] **Please open PR in `Draft` mode if it is:**
	- Work in progress or not intended to be merged.
	- Encountering multiple pipeline failures and working on fixes.
- [ ] If an SDK is being regenerated based on a new swagger spec, a link to the pull request containing these swagger spec changes has been included above.
- [ ] **I have read the [contribution guidelines](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-net/blob/main/CONTRIBUTING.md).**
- [ ] **The pull request does not introduce [breaking changes](https://github.com/dotnet/corefx/blob/master/Documentation/coding-guidelines/breaking-change-rules.md).**

### [General Guidelines and Best Practices](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-net/blob/main/CONTRIBUTING.md#general-guidelines)
- [ ] Title of the pull request is clear and informative.
- [ ] There are a small number of commits, each of which have an informative message. This means that previously merged commits do not appear in the history of the PR. For more information on cleaning up the commits in your PR, [see this page](https://github.com/Azure/azure-powershell/blob/master/documentation/development-docs/cleaning-up-commits.md).

### [Testing Guidelines](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-net/blob/main/CONTRIBUTING.md#testing-guidelines)
- [ ] Pull request includes test coverage for the included changes.

### [SDK Generation Guidelines](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-net/blob/main/CONTRIBUTING.md#sdk-generation-guidelines)
- [ ] The generate.cmd file for the SDK has been updated with the version of AutoRest, as well as the commitid of your swagger spec or link to the swagger spec, used to generate the code. (Track 2 only)
- [ ] The `*.csproj` and `AssemblyInfo.cs` files have been updated with the new version of the SDK. Please double check nuget.org current release version.

## Additional management plane SDK specific contribution checklist: 
Note: Only applies to `Microsoft.Azure.Management.[RP]` or `Azure.ResourceManager.[RP]`
 
- [ ] Include updated [management metadata](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-net/tree/main/eng/mgmt/mgmtmetadata).
- [ ] Update AzureRP.props to add/remove version info to maintain up to date API versions.

### Management plane SDK Troubleshooting
- If this is very first SDK for a services and you are adding new service folders directly under /SDK, please add `new service` label and/or contact assigned reviewer.
- If the check fails at the `Verify Code Generation` step, please ensure:
	- Do not modify any code in generated folders.
	- Do not selectively include/remove generated files in the PR.
	- Do use `generate.ps1/cmd` to generate this PR instead of calling `autorest` directly.
	Please pay attention to the @microsoft.csharp version output after running `generate.ps1`. If it is lower than current released version (2.3.82), please run it again as it should pull down the latest version.
	
	**Note: We have recently updated the PSH module called by `generate.ps1` to emit additional data. This would help reduce/eliminate the Code Verification check error. Please run following command**:

	    `dotnet msbuild eng/mgmt.proj /t:Util /p:UtilityName=InstallPsModules`

### Old outstanding PR cleanup
 Please note:
	If PRs (including draft) has been out for more than 60 days and there are no responses from our query or followups, they will be closed to maintain a concise list for our reviewers.

'active_lock_reason': None, 'body': '
[Enter feedback here]

The page states:
"If you want to add or remove geo-replication or read access to the secondary region, you can use the Azure portal, PowerShell, or Azure CLI to update the replication setting. However, if you want to change how data is replicated in the primary region, by moving from LRS to ZRS or vice versa, then you must perform a manual migration."

A switch from ZRS to GZRS does not affect how data is replicated in the primary region (it remains ZRS there) according to this page: https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/storage/common/storage-redundancy?toc=/azure/storage/blobs/toc.json

"Geo-zone-redundant storage (GZRS) copies your data synchronously across three Azure availability zones in the primary region using ZRS."

The primary region remains ZRS in the switch from ZRS -> GZRS. So, why can this not be done in the portal. The page does not mention the ZRS -> GZRS scenario under any of the subsections detailing how to perform the change. It only appears in the table as requiring a live migration without further explanation.

The table in the article explains that the account must be migrated with a live migration, unless the change is for a failback operation. We can also add a paragraph about this in the text; however, the guidance won't change.

We link out to the pricing page from the article. I understand that the pricing page isn't specific about migration, and that's because geo-replication will affect different storage accounts differently, depending on the amount of data that needs to be replicated. # All SDK Contribution checklist:

This checklist is used to make sure that common guidelines for a pull request are followed.
- [ ] **Please open PR in `Draft` mode if it is:**
	- Work in progress or not intended to be merged.
	- Encountering multiple pipeline failures and working on fixes.
- [ ] If an SDK is being regenerated based on a new swagger spec, a link to the pull request containing these swagger spec changes has been included above.
- [ ] **I have read the [contribution guidelines](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-net/blob/main/CONTRIBUTING.md).**
- [ ] **The pull request does not introduce [breaking changes](https://github.com/dotnet/corefx/blob/master/Documentation/coding-guidelines/breaking-change-rules.md).**

### [General Guidelines and Best Practices](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-net/blob/main/CONTRIBUTING.md#general-guidelines)
- [ ] Title of the pull request is clear and informative.
- [ ] There are a small number of commits, each of which have an informative message. This means that previously merged commits do not appear in the history of the PR. For more information on cleaning up the commits in your PR, [see this page](https://github.com/Azure/azure-powershell/blob/master/documentation/development-docs/cleaning-up-commits.md).

### [Testing Guidelines](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-net/blob/main/CONTRIBUTING.md#testing-guidelines)
- [ ] Pull request includes test coverage for the included changes.

### [SDK Generation Guidelines](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-net/blob/main/CONTRIBUTING.md#sdk-generation-guidelines)
- [ ] The generate.cmd file for the SDK has been updated with the version of AutoRest, as well as the commitid of your swagger spec or link to the swagger spec, used to generate the code. (Track 2 only)
- [ ] The `*.csproj` and `AssemblyInfo.cs` files have been updated with the new version of the SDK. Please double check nuget.org current release version.

## Additional management plane SDK specific contribution checklist: 
Note: Only applies to `Microsoft.Azure.Management.[RP]` or `Azure.ResourceManager.[RP]`
 
- [ ] Include updated [management metadata](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-net/tree/main/eng/mgmt/mgmtmetadata).
- [ ] Update AzureRP.props to add/remove version info to maintain up to date API versions.

### Management plane SDK Troubleshooting
- If this is very first SDK for a services and you are adding new service folders directly under /SDK, please add `new service` label and/or contact assigned reviewer.
- If the check fails at the `Verify Code Generation` step, please ensure:
	- Do not modify any code in generated folders.
	- Do not selectively include/remove generated files in the PR.
	- Do use `generate.ps1/cmd` to generate this PR instead of calling `autorest` directly.
	Please pay attention to the @microsoft.csharp version output after running `generate.ps1`. If it is lower than current released version (2.3.82), please run it again as it should pull down the latest version.
	
	**Note: We have recently updated the PSH module called by `generate.ps1` to emit additional data. This would help reduce/eliminate the Code Verification check error. Please run following command**:

	    `dotnet msbuild eng/mgmt.proj /t:Util /p:UtilityName=InstallPsModules`

### Old outstanding PR cleanup
 Please note:
	If PRs (including draft) has been out for more than 60 days and there are no responses from our query or followups, they will be closed to maintain a concise list for our reviewers.

# All SDK Contribution checklist:

This checklist is used to make sure that common guidelines for a pull request are followed.
- [ ] **Please open PR in `Draft` mode if it is:**
	- Work in progress or not intended to be merged.
	- Encountering multiple pipeline failures and working on fixes.
- [ ] If an SDK is being regenerated based on a new swagger spec, a link to the pull request containing these swagger spec changes has been included above.
- [ ] **I have read the [contribution guidelines](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-net/blob/main/CONTRIBUTING.md).**
- [ ] **The pull request does not introduce [breaking changes](https://github.com/dotnet/corefx/blob/master/Documentation/coding-guidelines/breaking-change-rules.md).**

### [General Guidelines and Best Practices](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-net/blob/main/CONTRIBUTING.md#general-guidelines)
- [ ] Title of the pull request is clear and informative.
- [ ] There are a small number of commits, each of which have an informative message. This means that previously merged commits do not appear in the history of the PR. For more information on cleaning up the commits in your PR, [see this page](https://github.com/Azure/azure-powershell/blob/master/documentation/development-docs/cleaning-up-commits.md).

### [Testing Guidelines](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-net/blob/main/CONTRIBUTING.md#testing-guidelines)
- [ ] Pull request includes test coverage for the included changes.

### [SDK Generation Guidelines](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-net/blob/main/CONTRIBUTING.md#sdk-generation-guidelines)
- [ ] The generate.cmd file for the SDK has been updated with the version of AutoRest, as well as the commitid of your swagger spec or link to the swagger spec, used to generate the code. (Track 2 only)
- [ ] The `*.csproj` and `AssemblyInfo.cs` files have been updated with the new version of the SDK. Please double check nuget.org current release version.

## Additional management plane SDK specific contribution checklist: 
Note: Only applies to `Microsoft.Azure.Management.[RP]` or `Azure.ResourceManager.[RP]`
 
- [ ] Include updated [management metadata](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-net/tree/main/eng/mgmt/mgmtmetadata).
- [ ] Update AzureRP.props to add/remove version info to maintain up to date API versions.

### Management plane SDK Troubleshooting
- If this is very first SDK for a services and you are adding new service folders directly under /SDK, please add `new service` label and/or contact assigned reviewer.
- If the check fails at the `Verify Code Generation` step, please ensure:
	- Do not modify any code in generated folders.
	- Do not selectively include/remove generated files in the PR.
	- Do use `generate.ps1/cmd` to generate this PR instead of calling `autorest` directly.
	Please pay attention to the @microsoft.csharp version output after running `generate.ps1`. If it is lower than current released version (2.3.82), please run it again as it should pull down the latest version.
	
	**Note: We have recently updated the PSH module called by `generate.ps1` to emit additional data. This would help reduce/eliminate the Code Verification check error. Please run following command**:

	    `dotnet msbuild eng/mgmt.proj /t:Util /p:UtilityName=InstallPsModules`

### Old outstanding PR cleanup
 Please note:
	If PRs (including draft) has been out for more than 60 days and there are no responses from our query or followups, they will be closed to maintain a concise list for our reviewers.

# All SDK Contribution checklist:

This checklist is used to make sure that common guidelines for a pull request are followed.
- [ ] **Please open PR in `Draft` mode if it is:**
	- Work in progress or not intended to be merged.
	- Encountering multiple pipeline failures and working on fixes.
- [ ] If an SDK is being regenerated based on a new swagger spec, a link to the pull request containing these swagger spec changes has been included above.
- [ ] **I have read the [contribution guidelines](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-net/blob/main/CONTRIBUTING.md).**
- [ ] **The pull request does not introduce [breaking changes](https://github.com/dotnet/corefx/blob/master/Documentation/coding-guidelines/breaking-change-rules.md).**

### [General Guidelines and Best Practices](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-net/blob/main/CONTRIBUTING.md#general-guidelines)
- [ ] Title of the pull request is clear and informative.
- [ ] There are a small number of commits, each of which have an informative message. This means that previously merged commits do not appear in the history of the PR. For more information on cleaning up the commits in your PR, [see this page](https://github.com/Azure/azure-powershell/blob/master/documentation/development-docs/cleaning-up-commits.md).

### [Testing Guidelines](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-net/blob/main/CONTRIBUTING.md#testing-guidelines)
- [ ] Pull request includes test coverage for the included changes.

### [SDK Generation Guidelines](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-net/blob/main/CONTRIBUTING.md#sdk-generation-guidelines)
- [ ] The generate.cmd file for the SDK has been updated with the version of AutoRest, as well as the commitid of your swagger spec or link to the swagger spec, used to generate the code. (Track 2 only)
- [ ] The `*.csproj` and `AssemblyInfo.cs` files have been updated with the new version of the SDK. Please double check nuget.org current release version.

## Additional management plane SDK specific contribution checklist: 
Note: Only applies to `Microsoft.Azure.Management.[RP]` or `Azure.ResourceManager.[RP]`
 
- [ ] Include updated [management metadata](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-net/tree/main/eng/mgmt/mgmtmetadata).
- [ ] Update AzureRP.props to add/remove version info to maintain up to date API versions.

### Management plane SDK Troubleshooting
- If this is very first SDK for a services and you are adding new service folders directly under /SDK, please add `new service` label and/or contact assigned reviewer.
- If the check fails at the `Verify Code Generation` step, please ensure:
	- Do not modify any code in generated folders.
	- Do not selectively include/remove generated files in the PR.
	- Do use `generate.ps1/cmd` to generate this PR instead of calling `autorest` directly.
	Please pay attention to the @microsoft.csharp version output after running `generate.ps1`. If it is lower than current released version (2.3.82), please run it again as it should pull down the latest version.
	
	**Note: We have recently updated the PSH module called by `generate.ps1` to emit additional data. This would help reduce/eliminate the Code Verification check error. Please run following command**:

	    `dotnet msbuild eng/mgmt.proj /t:Util /p:UtilityName=InstallPsModules`

### Old outstanding PR cleanup
 Please note:
	If PRs (including draft) has been out for more than 60 days and there are no responses from our query or followups, they will be closed to maintain a concise list for our reviewers.

# All SDK Contribution checklist:

This checklist is used to make sure that common guidelines for a pull request are followed.
- [ ] **Please open PR in `Draft` mode if it is:**
	- Work in progress or not intended to be merged.
	- Encountering multiple pipeline failures and working on fixes.
- [ ] If an SDK is being regenerated based on a new swagger spec, a link to the pull request containing these swagger spec changes has been included above.
- [ ] **I have read the [contribution guidelines](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-net/blob/main/CONTRIBUTING.md).**
- [ ] **The pull request does not introduce [breaking changes](https://github.com/dotnet/corefx/blob/master/Documentation/coding-guidelines/breaking-change-rules.md).**

### [General Guidelines and Best Practices](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-net/blob/main/CONTRIBUTING.md#general-guidelines)
- [ ] Title of the pull request is clear and informative.
- [ ] There are a small number of commits, each of which have an informative message. This means that previously merged commits do not appear in the history of the PR. For more information on cleaning up the commits in your PR, [see this page](https://github.com/Azure/azure-powershell/blob/master/documentation/development-docs/cleaning-up-commits.md).

### [Testing Guidelines](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-net/blob/main/CONTRIBUTING.md#testing-guidelines)
- [ ] Pull request includes test coverage for the included changes.

### [SDK Generation Guidelines](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-net/blob/main/CONTRIBUTING.md#sdk-generation-guidelines)
- [ ] The generate.cmd file for the SDK has been updated with the version of AutoRest, as well as the commitid of your swagger spec or link to the swagger spec, used to generate the code. (Track 2 only)
- [ ] The `*.csproj` and `AssemblyInfo.cs` files have been updated with the new version of the SDK. Please double check nuget.org current release version.

## Additional management plane SDK specific contribution checklist: 
Note: Only applies to `Microsoft.Azure.Management.[RP]` or `Azure.ResourceManager.[RP]`
 
- [ ] Include updated [management metadata](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-net/tree/main/eng/mgmt/mgmtmetadata).
- [ ] Update AzureRP.props to add/remove version info to maintain up to date API versions.

### Management plane SDK Troubleshooting
- If this is very first SDK for a services and you are adding new service folders directly under /SDK, please add `new service` label and/or contact assigned reviewer.
- If the check fails at the `Verify Code Generation` step, please ensure:
	- Do not modify any code in generated folders.
	- Do not selectively include/remove generated files in the PR.
	- Do use `generate.ps1/cmd` to generate this PR instead of calling `autorest` directly.
	Please pay attention to the @microsoft.csharp version output after running `generate.ps1`. If it is lower than current released version (2.3.82), please run it again as it should pull down the latest version.
	
	**Note: We have recently updated the PSH module called by `generate.ps1` to emit additional data. This would help reduce/eliminate the Code Verification check error. Please run following command**:

	    `dotnet msbuild eng/mgmt.proj /t:Util /p:UtilityName=InstallPsModules`

### Old outstanding PR cleanup
 Please note:
	If PRs (including draft) has been out for more than 60 days and there are no responses from our query or followups, they will be closed to maintain a concise list for our reviewers.

This checklist is used to make sure that common guidelines for a pull request are followed.

### [General Guidelines and Best Practices](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-net/blob/main/CONTRIBUTING.md#general-guidelines)

### [Testing Guidelines](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-net/blob/main/CONTRIBUTING.md#testing-guidelines)

### [SDK Generation Guidelines](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-net/blob/main/CONTRIBUTING.md#sdk-generation-guidelines)

- If this is very first SDK for a services and you are adding new service folders directly under /SDK, please add `new service` label and/or contact assigned reviewer.

	- Do not selectively include/remove generated files in the PR.

	Please pay attention to the @microsoft.csharp version output after running `generate.ps1`. If it is lower than current released version (2.3.82), please run it again as it should pull down the latest version.

# All SDK Contribution checklist:

This checklist is used to make sure that common guidelines for a pull request are followed.
- [ ] **Please open PR in `Draft` mode if it is:**
	- Work in progress or not intended to be merged.
	- Encountering multiple pipeline failures and working on fixes.
- [ ] If an SDK is being regenerated based on a new swagger spec, a link to the pull request containing these swagger spec changes has been included above.
- [ ] **I have read the [contribution guidelines](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-net/blob/main/CONTRIBUTING.md).**
- [ ] **The pull request does not introduce [breaking changes](https://github.com/dotnet/corefx/blob/master/Documentation/coding-guidelines/breaking-change-rules.md).**

### [General Guidelines and Best Practices](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-net/blob/main/CONTRIBUTING.md#general-guidelines)
- [ ] Title of the pull request is clear and informative.
- [ ] There are a small number of commits, each of which have an informative message. This means that previously merged commits do not appear in the history of the PR. For more information on cleaning up the commits in your PR, [see this page](https://github.com/Azure/azure-powershell/blob/master/documentation/development-docs/cleaning-up-commits.md).

### [Testing Guidelines](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-net/blob/main/CONTRIBUTING.md#testing-guidelines)
- [ ] Pull request includes test coverage for the included changes.

### [SDK Generation Guidelines](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-net/blob/main/CONTRIBUTING.md#sdk-generation-guidelines)
- [ ] The generate.cmd file for the SDK has been updated with the version of AutoRest, as well as the commitid of your swagger spec or link to the swagger spec, used to generate the code. (Track 2 only)
- [ ] The `*.csproj` and `AssemblyInfo.cs` files have been updated with the new version of the SDK. Please double check nuget.org current release version.

## Additional management plane SDK specific contribution checklist: 
Note: Only applies to `Microsoft.Azure.Management.[RP]` or `Azure.ResourceManager.[RP]`
 
- [ ] Include updated [management metadata](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-net/tree/main/eng/mgmt/mgmtmetadata).
- [ ] Update AzureRP.props to add/remove version info to maintain up to date API versions.

### Management plane SDK Troubleshooting
- If this is very first SDK for a services and you are adding new service folders directly under /SDK, please add `new service` label and/or contact assigned reviewer.
- If the check fails at the `Verify Code Generation` step, please ensure:
	- Do not modify any code in generated folders.
	- Do not selectively include/remove generated files in the PR.
	- Do use `generate.ps1/cmd` to generate this PR instead of calling `autorest` directly.
	Please pay attention to the @microsoft.csharp version output after running `generate.ps1`. If it is lower than current released version (2.3.82), please run it again as it should pull down the latest version.
	
	**Note: We have recently updated the PSH module called by `generate.ps1` to emit additional data. This would help reduce/eliminate the Code Verification check error. Please run following command**:

	    `dotnet msbuild eng/mgmt.proj /t:Util /p:UtilityName=InstallPsModules`

### Old outstanding PR cleanup
 Please note:
	If PRs (including draft) has been out for more than 60 days and there are no responses from our query or followups, they will be closed to maintain a concise list for our reviewers.

# All SDK Contribution checklist:

This checklist is used to make sure that common guidelines for a pull request are followed.
- [ ] **Please open PR in `Draft` mode if it is:**
	- Work in progress or not intended to be merged.
	- Encountering multiple pipeline failures and working on fixes.
- [ ] If an SDK is being regenerated based on a new swagger spec, a link to the pull request containing these swagger spec changes has been included above.
- [ ] **I have read the [contribution guidelines](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-net/blob/main/CONTRIBUTING.md).**
- [ ] **The pull request does not introduce [breaking changes](https://github.com/dotnet/corefx/blob/master/Documentation/coding-guidelines/breaking-change-rules.md).**

### [General Guidelines and Best Practices](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-net/blob/main/CONTRIBUTING.md#general-guidelines)
- [ ] Title of the pull request is clear and informative.
- [ ] There are a small number of commits, each of which have an informative message. This means that previously merged commits do not appear in the history of the PR. For more information on cleaning up the commits in your PR, [see this page](https://github.com/Azure/azure-powershell/blob/master/documentation/development-docs/cleaning-up-commits.md).

### [Testing Guidelines](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-net/blob/main/CONTRIBUTING.md#testing-guidelines)
- [ ] Pull request includes test coverage for the included changes.

### [SDK Generation Guidelines](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-net/blob/main/CONTRIBUTING.md#sdk-generation-guidelines)
- [ ] The generate.cmd file for the SDK has been updated with the version of AutoRest, as well as the commitid of your swagger spec or link to the swagger spec, used to generate the code. (Track 2 only)
- [ ] The `*.csproj` and `AssemblyInfo.cs` files have been updated with the new version of the SDK. Please double check nuget.org current release version.

## Additional management plane SDK specific contribution checklist: 
Note: Only applies to `Microsoft.Azure.Management.[RP]` or `Azure.ResourceManager.[RP]`
 
- [ ] Include updated [management metadata](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-net/tree/main/eng/mgmt/mgmtmetadata).
- [ ] Update AzureRP.props to add/remove version info to maintain up to date API versions.

### Management plane SDK Troubleshooting
- If this is very first SDK for a services and you are adding new service folders directly under /SDK, please add `new service` label and/or contact assigned reviewer.
- If the check fails at the `Verify Code Generation` step, please ensure:
	- Do not modify any code in generated folders.
	- Do not selectively include/remove generated files in the PR.
	- Do use `generate.ps1/cmd` to generate this PR instead of calling `autorest` directly.
	Please pay attention to the @microsoft.csharp version output after running `generate.ps1`. If it is lower than current released version (2.3.82), please run it again as it should pull down the latest version.
	
	**Note: We have recently updated the PSH module called by `generate.ps1` to emit additional data. This would help reduce/eliminate the Code Verification check error. Please run following command**:

	    `dotnet msbuild eng/mgmt.proj /t:Util /p:UtilityName=InstallPsModules`

### Old outstanding PR cleanup
 Please note:
	If PRs (including draft) has been out for more than 60 days and there are no responses from our query or followups, they will be closed to maintain a concise list for our reviewers.

# All SDK Contribution checklist:

This checklist is used to make sure that common guidelines for a pull request are followed.
- [ ] **Please open PR in `Draft` mode if it is:**
	- Work in progress or not intended to be merged.
	- Encountering multiple pipeline failures and working on fixes.
- [ ] If an SDK is being regenerated based on a new swagger spec, a link to the pull request containing these swagger spec changes has been included above.
- [ ] **I have read the [contribution guidelines](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-net/blob/main/CONTRIBUTING.md).**
- [ ] **The pull request does not introduce [breaking changes](https://github.com/dotnet/corefx/blob/master/Documentation/coding-guidelines/breaking-change-rules.md).**

### [General Guidelines and Best Practices](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-net/blob/main/CONTRIBUTING.md#general-guidelines)
- [ ] Title of the pull request is clear and informative.
- [ ] There are a small number of commits, each of which have an informative message. This means that previously merged commits do not appear in the history of the PR. For more information on cleaning up the commits in your PR, [see this page](https://github.com/Azure/azure-powershell/blob/master/documentation/development-docs/cleaning-up-commits.md).

### [Testing Guidelines](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-net/blob/main/CONTRIBUTING.md#testing-guidelines)
- [ ] Pull request includes test coverage for the included changes.

### [SDK Generation Guidelines](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-net/blob/main/CONTRIBUTING.md#sdk-generation-guidelines)
- [ ] The generate.cmd file for the SDK has been updated with the version of AutoRest, as well as the commitid of your swagger spec or link to the swagger spec, used to generate the code. (Track 2 only)
- [ ] The `*.csproj` and `AssemblyInfo.cs` files have been updated with the new version of the SDK. Please double check nuget.org current release version.

## Additional management plane SDK specific contribution checklist: 
Note: Only applies to `Microsoft.Azure.Management.[RP]` or `Azure.ResourceManager.[RP]`
 
- [ ] Include updated [management metadata](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-net/tree/main/eng/mgmt/mgmtmetadata).
- [ ] Update AzureRP.props to add/remove version info to maintain up to date API versions.

### Management plane SDK Troubleshooting
- If this is very first SDK for a services and you are adding new service folders directly under /SDK, please add `new service` label and/or contact assigned reviewer.
- If the check fails at the `Verify Code Generation` step, please ensure:
	- Do not modify any code in generated folders.
	- Do not selectively include/remove generated files in the PR.
	- Do use `generate.ps1/cmd` to generate this PR instead of calling `autorest` directly.
	Please pay attention to the @microsoft.csharp version output after running `generate.ps1`. If it is lower than current released version (2.3.82), please run it again as it should pull down the latest version.
	
	**Note: We have recently updated the PSH module called by `generate.ps1` to emit additional data. This would help reduce/eliminate the Code Verification check error. Please run following command**:

	    `dotnet msbuild eng/mgmt.proj /t:Util /p:UtilityName=InstallPsModules`

### Old outstanding PR cleanup
 Please note:
	If PRs (including draft) has been out for more than 60 days and there are no responses from our query or followups, they will be closed to maintain a concise list for our reviewers.
